            "id": "intro_min_max_sum",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "Min, Max & Sum",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 1
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "When working with lists of numbers, you often need to find the smallest value, largest value, or add them all up. Python provides built-in functions for these common tasks."
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "These functions make it easy to analyze numerical data in lists."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "min_function",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "Finding the Minimum",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 2
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "The `min()` function finds the **smallest value** in a list."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "numbers = [45, 12, 78, 23, 67]\nsmallest = min(numbers)\nprint(f\"Smallest number: {smallest}\")",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "The smallest number is 12"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "`min()` found that `12` is the smallest number in the list."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "min_negative",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "`min()` works with negative numbers too. The most negative number is the smallest."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "temperatures = [15, -5, 20, -10, 8]\nlowest = min(temperatures)\nprint(f\"Lowest temperature: {lowest}\")",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "Lowest temperature: -10"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "`-10` is the smallest (most negative) value in the list."
                }
            ]
        },
